<subSubSection id="6DC56513FFF3FFFFE292A39FCC3F7759" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="25603698FFF3FFFFE292A39FCA247679" blockId="29.[151,1437,504,1467]" box="[151,1124,504,531]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE292A39FCFE17678" bold="true" box="[151,417,504,531]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">
<typeStatus id="FA64883AFFF3FFFFE292A39FCE927679" box="[151,210,505,531]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Type</typeStatus>
and only species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE3ADA39ECD7B7679" authority="Scudder, 1890" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1890" box="[424,827,504,531]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stricta">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE3ADA39ECCD17678" box="[424,657,504,530]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa stricta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE092A39ECD7B7679" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[663,827,504,531]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 734" refId="ref25710" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1890) The Tertiary insects of North America. Report of the United States Geological Survey of the Territories, 13, 1 - 734, 28 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 44698" type="journal article" year="1890">Scudder, 1890</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by subsequent monotypy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25603698FFF3FFFFE2C2A07BCC3F7759" blockId="29.[151,1437,504,1467]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE2C2A07BCFF9765C" bold="true" box="[199,441,540,567]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Emended diagnosis.</emphasis>
May be distinguished from other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE1C3A07ACA37765C" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1910" box="[966,1143,540,566]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nothochrysinae">Nothochrysinae</taxonomicName>
by a combination of the following. Fore- and hind wings: (1) two gradate series in radial space [
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE1D8A026CAEA7630" authorityName="Makarkin &amp; Archibald" authorityYear="2013" box="[989,1194,576,602]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Okanaganochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE1D8A026CAEA7630" box="[989,1194,576,602]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Okanaganochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE6B9A026CB0B7630" authorityName="Kimmins" authorityYear="1952" box="[1212,1355,576,602]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Triplochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE6B9A026CB0B7630" box="[1212,1355,576,602]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Triplochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: three; 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE292A002CF6C7614" authorityName="Esben-Petersen" authorityYear="1917" box="[151,300,612,638]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Dictyochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE292A002CF6C7614" box="[151,300,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Dictyochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE339A002CFA17614" authorityName="Makarkin &amp; Archibald" authorityYear="2013" box="[316,481,612,638]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Adamsochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE339A002CFA17614" box="[316,481,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Adamsochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: four or more]; (2) inner gradate series arranged in strongly broken line (shared by 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE292A0EECF5E76C8" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[151,286,648,674]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE292A0EECF5E76C8" box="[151,286,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, some 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE369A0EECFBB76C8" authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1868" box="[364,507,648,674]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Nothochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE369A0EECFBB76C8" box="[364,507,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Nothochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE02AA0EECC8E76C8" authorityName="Schluter" authorityYear="1982" box="[559,718,648,674]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Cimbrochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE02AA0EECC8E76C8" box="[559,718,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Cimbrochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) [other genera: arranged in smooth line]; (3) Psm nearly straight, very slightly zigzagged [
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE3B7A0CACC7976AC" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[434,569,684,710]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE3B7A0CACC7976AC" box="[434,569,684,710]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: strongly zigzagged]; (4) Psm formed by five branches of RP [
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE708A0CACBD476AC" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[1293,1428,684,710]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE708A0CACBD476AC" box="[1293,1428,684,710]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: two-three branches]. Forewing: (5) 
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE02CA0B7CC057680" box="[553,581,721,746]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">im</emphasis>
elongate [
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE0B8A0B6CD1C7680" authorityName="Schluter" authorityYear="1982" box="[701,860,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Cimbrochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE0B8A0B6CD1C7680" box="[701,860,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Cimbrochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE16EA0B6CDB47680" authorityName="Wilmann" authorityYear="1993" box="[875,1012,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Danochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE16EA0B6CDB47680" box="[875,1012,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Danochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE607A0B6CA3E7680" authorityName="Makarkin" authorityYear="2014" box="[1026,1150,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Asiachrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE607A0B6CA3E7680" box="[1026,1150,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Asiachrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE688A0B6CB1A7680" authorityName="Makarkin &amp; Archibald" authorityYear="2013" box="[1165,1370,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Okanaganochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE688A0B6CB1A7680" box="[1165,1370,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Okanaganochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE76CA0B7CEB77764" authorityName="Adams &amp; Penny" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Leptochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE76CA0B7CEB77764" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Leptochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: broadly pentagonal; 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE3F4A092CCEB7764" authorityName="Wilmann" authorityYear="1993" box="[497,683,756,782]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Stephenbrooksia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE3F4A092CCEB7764" box="[497,683,756,782]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Stephenbrooksia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: very long, narrow]. Hind wing: three branches of CuA proximad fusion with MP [
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE350A17ECFA47758" authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1868" box="[341,484,792,818]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Nothochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE350A17ECFA47758" box="[341,484,792,818]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Nothochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: one branch].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6DC56513FFF3FFFFE2C2A15BCD8271D1" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25603698FFF3FFFFE2C2A15BCF5070F1" blockId="29.[151,1437,504,1467]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE2C2A15BCF7B773D" bold="true" box="[199,315,829,855]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Remarks.</emphasis>
It has been generally considered that the genera 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE16EA15ACDB2773C" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[875,1010,828,854]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE16EA15ACDB2773C" box="[875,1010,828,854]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE62EA15ACA85773C" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1882" box="[1067,1221,828,854]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE62EA15ACA85773C" box="[1067,1221,828,854]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were described by 
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE292A106CF077711" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[151,327,864,891]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="721 - 831" refId="ref25635" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1885) Systematische Ubersicht der fossilen Myriopoden, Arachnoideen und Insekten. In: Zittel, K. A., Handbuch der Palaeontologie. Abt. 1. Palaeozoologie. Bd 2. Mollusca und Arthropoda. Verlag von R. Oldenbourg, Munchen, Leipzig, pp. 721 - 831. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 2492" type="book chapter" year="1885">Scudder (1885)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE386A106CC737711" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[387,563,864,891]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 734" refId="ref25710" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1890) The Tertiary insects of North America. Report of the United States Geological Survey of the Territories, 13, 1 - 734, 28 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 44698" type="journal article" year="1890">Scudder (1890)</bibRefCitation>
respectively (
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE0D2A107CCB87710" box="[727,760,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">e.g</emphasis>
., 
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE10BA106CDE37711" author="Adams, P. A." box="[782,931,864,891]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="215 - 238" refId="ref21987" refString="Adams, P. A. (1967) A review of the Mesochrysinae and Nothochrysinae (Neuroptera: Chrysopidae). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 135, 215 - 238." type="journal article" year="1967">Adams 1967</bibRefCitation>
). However, they were actually described by Scudder in 1883 when these names were provided with short diagnoses: “the genera differ from each other in the course of the upper cubital vein [= Psm proximally, and inner gradate series of crossveins distally], which in 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE292A1AACF71778C" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1882" box="[151,305,972,998]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE292A1AACF71778C" box="[151,305,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is direct and bordered by comparatively uniform cells, while in 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE609A1AACAD3778C" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[1036,1171,972,998]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE609A1AACAD3778C" box="[1036,1171,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is doubly bent in the middle, and is therefore bordered by very unequal cells” (
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE11AA196CDFF7061" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[799,959,1008,1035]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="271 - 293" refId="ref25580" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1883) The tertiary Lake Basin at Florissant, Colo., between South and Hayden Parks. Annual Report of the United States Geological and Geographical Survey of the Territories, 12, 271 - 293. https: // doi. org / 10.3133 / 70159191" type="journal article" year="1883">Scudder 1883</bibRefCitation>
: p. 283). Although he included no species, these genus names were available according to ICZN Article 67.2.2. The first species expressly included in these genera were 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE32DA65ECC977039" authority="Scudder, 1885" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1885" box="[296,727,1080,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE32DA65ECC6C7038" box="[296,556,1080,1106]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa inaequalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE036A65ECC977039" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[563,727,1080,1107]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="721 - 831" refId="ref25635" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1885) Systematische Ubersicht der fossilen Myriopoden, Arachnoideen und Insekten. In: Zittel, K. A., Handbuch der Palaeontologie. Abt. 1. Palaeozoologie. Bd 2. Mollusca und Arthropoda. Verlag von R. Oldenbourg, Munchen, Leipzig, pp. 721 - 831. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 2492" type="book chapter" year="1885">Scudder, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE116A65ECAE87039" authority="Scudder, 1890" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1890" box="[787,1192,1080,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stricta">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE116A65ECDBD7038" box="[787,1021,1080,1106]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa stricta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFF3FFFFE601A65ECAE87039" author="Scudder, S. H." box="[1028,1192,1080,1107]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 734" refId="ref25710" refString="Scudder, S. H. (1890) The Tertiary insects of North America. Report of the United States Geological Survey of the Territories, 13, 1 - 734, 28 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 44698" type="journal article" year="1890">Scudder, 1890</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. These are deemed to be the only originally included nominal species, and are, therefore, the 
<typeStatus id="FA64883AFFF3FFFFE1BEA63BCDAB701D" box="[955,1003,1117,1143]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">type</typeStatus>
species by subsequent monotypy (Article 69.3).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25603698FFF3FFFFE2C2A6C3CD8271D1" blockId="29.[151,1437,504,1467]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">
Upon our examination of the 
<typeStatus id="FA64883AFFF3FFFFE01DA6C2CC3A70D4" box="[536,634,1188,1214]" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE0A7A6C2CDCC70D4" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1890" box="[674,908,1188,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stricta">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE0A7A6C2CDCC70D4" box="[674,908,1188,1214]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa stricta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we find that Scudder’s diagnosis (1883) does not separate these genera, and his drawings (1890, Pl. 14, 
<figureCitation id="BDE42A1DFFF3FFFFE12DA6AECD3E7089" box="[808,894,1224,1251]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[194,1385,194,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-17@18.[190,1397,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Wing venation drawings of Cimbrochrysa major sp. nov., paratype FLFO 4194 (male). A, left forewing; B, right forewing; C, right hind wings; D, left hind wing. Scale bar = 3 mm (all to scale)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6522489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6522489/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Figs 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="BDE42A1DFFF3FFFFE18EA6AFCDE87089" box="[907,936,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1946,1970]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,512,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-167@20.[162,1426,512,1922]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 14. Lithochrysa wickhami (Cockerell, 1914), holotype MCZ 4499 (male?). A, specimen; B, right forewing; C, left forewing; D, right hind wing; E, left hind wing; F, end of abdomen. All converted to standard view, with apex to the right. s, unknown structure, Scale bars = 3 mm (A; B–E to scales), 1 mm (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6522491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6522491/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">14</figureCitation>
) which depict the inner gradate series in the fore- and hind wing as smoothly aligned are inaccurate. We, therefore, provide the above emended diagnosis. The gradate series of crossveins in 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE3FAA776CCD97140" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1882" box="[511,665,1296,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE3FAA776CCD97140" box="[511,665,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE0D3A776CD1D7140" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[726,861,1296,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE0D3A776CD1D7140" box="[726,861,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similarly arranged in both the fore- and hind wings, with the inner series of crossveins arranged in a strongly broken line, which is shifted anteriad at the termination of Psm. These genera differ as in the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE13DA73ECDFF7118" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1883" box="[824,959,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE13DA73ECDFF7118" box="[824,959,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Tribochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, below. It is interesting that the hind wing venation of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE319A71ACFF671FC" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1882" box="[284,438,1404,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Palaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE319A71ACFF671FC" box="[284,438,1404,1430]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Palaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE0C9A71ACD1B71FC" authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1868" box="[716,859,1404,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Nothochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFF3FFFFE0C9A71ACD1B71FC" box="[716,859,1404,1430]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="330">Nothochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFF3FFFFE195A71ACA6071FC" baseAuthorityName="Semeria &amp; Nel" baseAuthorityYear="1990" box="[912,1056,1404,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chrysopinae">Chrysopinae</taxonomicName>
, mainly by the arrangement of the inner gradate series of crossveins together with the well-developed Psm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
